"Many of my inmate students believed and acted upon the belief that these types of inmates automatically deserved constant punishment (above and beyond being incarcerated). No. That's vengeance.  Justice is giving someone their due, restoring to victims what was taken.  That's why our justice system, any justice system, is necessarily inadequate.  It's not possible to unmurder, unrape, or otherwise unabuse people and un-all the horrors that come with those evils.  True justice, complete justice, perfect justice with respect to punishment as well as the restorative aspect necessarily requires God-like power and a certain degree of mercy from the victimized.  Anything less fails.  Incarceration and monetary "compensation", sadly, are the best we can do.  That doesn't mean we're not obliged to strive for an ever more perfect system of justice, however, any improvement, if any, could only be incremental and limited at best.  Moreover, greater risk exists for further injustice when we experience just outrage and so we must carefully scrutinize every adjudication or adjustments to the adjudication process in part or in whole.  Evil elicits vengeance, and vengeance  begets vengeance, until someone intervense and lets go of the just offense in a recognizable act of compassion.  This not only stops the vengeance cycle, but calls human consciousness to a higher ideal, a higher sense of collective self.  This is the only road to personal and societal peace.  Ronnie will receive his punishment, and from man, it can only be imperfect.  If we were to encourage or facilitate in any way his torture or murder, in an eye for an eye sentencing, it would only serve to lower us into becoming a society of Ronnies.   We'd become equally unjust, equally ruthless, equally evil, equally guilty and diminished in our humanity.

Life in prison does mean you're spending the rest of your natural life in prison. However, in the event that the person can find a legal technicality/loophole, or otherwise manage to convince a different judge his sentence was too harsh, life sentences can (sometimes) be downgraded to allow the person a chance to leave prison. 

3 life sentences plus 90 years means that even if he manages to successfully appeal one life sentence, he'll still have the second one to serve. And if he successfully appeals that one, he has the third one to serve. And if he successfully appeals that one, he still has 90 years to serve. Appealing just one life sentence is very difficult, but it is possible. So with each additional life sentence, it dramatically decreases the odds of him ever seeing the outside of a prison wall again.
